<br>
1. The most important thing for a wizard is to *ALWAYS* stay close to the chanter.  By AE'ing you are generating a lot of aggro and if you are in between the chanter and the mobs you will also get proximity aggro.  Even if you are within range of the chanters stuns it is possible for mobs to be on the far side of you out of range of those stuns.  They will go to town!  So stay as close as possible.  Jyll's spells actually have a good range on them so you don't have to be in the middle of the pack provided they're &quot;stacked&quot; well.<br>
<br>
2. YOU have the best tool for bringing a scattered crowd into a tight &quot;stack&quot; to make everyone's jobs easier.  The Jyll's line of spells have a built-in knockback effect that over the course of a few AE's can move mobs a good distance.  It is important to realize that they are pushed not backwards from the direction they are facing, but simply in the direction YOU are facing.  So pick a corner to pull to, jam the chanter in the corner, and face the corner when AE'ing.  F9 out if you want to look around.  This will allow you to pull mobs into the corner instead of pushing them out from it.  This packs them tighter instead of spreading them out.  It also brings them closer to you and the chanter instead of pushing them away so you don't have to chase them around or worry about mobs going out of range of stuns or AE's.  If you do not have a corner or at least a wall to push mobs against, you can balance pushes against other AE'ers and the chanter to avoid lengthy migrations.  (Chanter stuns also push, but not nearly as much as Jyll's)  <br>
<br>
3. Corners are your chanter's best friend.  If your chanter(s) can get their buttocks wedged firmly into a corner they become much more resistant to interrupts since they won't have to worry about correcting for mobs that are pushing them.  This means you can pull larger trains with a single chanter.  <br>
<br>
4. Get between the mobs and your chanter if you only have one.  This lets you take some of the proximity aggro off the chanter and effectively tank for him/her. Yes, the chanter probably has a crapload more AC and HP than you because most members of their profession concentrate on that more than mana items.  However, YOU will take much less damage tanking for a chanter that is getting constant stuns off then you will take when your chanter is getting interrupted by mobs that could be hitting you instead.  This isn't a big deal when you have 2 enchanters however.<br>
<br>
5. On group composition:<br>
Druids have okay AE's.  They're a lot slower than mages or wizards, but will do in a pinch.  Clerics actually have a okay line of AE's too that are NOT limited to undead mobs.  For example the level 59 AE does over 600 damage with just a 1 second casting time.  The recast is atrocious however.  I AE'd for many levels without ever grouping with a wizard as an enchanter so don't assume you can't get by with other classes.  The number one underestimated AE class is bards however.  They have PB AE DoT's that can actually wrack up a ton of damage if a battle lasts a while.<br>
<br>
